{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958020701/0155.xml":{"full_text":"Guild Dance\nContinued from Page 1\ncert\u201d will be accompanied by a\ncontinuous comedy patter.\nGregory will also play th*\nelectric theramin. This unusua\ninstrument has been widely usec\non television programs and tc\nproduce special sound effects fo\nTV and motion picture dramas\nGregory is one of the few whc\nhas mastered the theramin and\ncan play it with the technique\nof a musician.\nA new feature this year wil\u2019\nbe the presentation of a half\nhour of drills and specialties by\nunits of the Marilynettes, na\ntionally famous awardwinning\nToledo marching corps, from\n7:30 to 8. This pre-dance enter\ntainment is provided for those\nwho get to the dance prior to\nthe 8 o'clock starting time.\nAt 10 o\u2019clock, the $1,000 in\ndoor prizes will be given away.\nThe top prize is $400 with the\nbalance divided into $300, $200\nand $100 prizes. Your ticket of\nadmission, of course, entitles you\nto a chance on all four prizes.\nContest Winner\nFollowing the drawing, there\nwill be the announcement of the\nwinner of the lyric-writing con\ntest sponsored by the Guild ear\nlier this year.\nThe purpose of the contest was\nto develop a theme song for the\nannual dance- and the words\nwere written for the familiar\nand appropriate song, \"Heart of\nMy Heart.\u201d\nThe winner will be awarded a\n$100 U.S. Savings Bond and the\nsong with the winning words\nwill then be sung by 7-year-old\nDenise Peksa, a talented Toledo\nyoungster who has appeared on\nnumerous local radio and TV\nprograms. She is the daughter\nof Mrs. John Peksa, a member of\nthe Guild.\nThe Camp was founded on\nthe belief that every child has a\nright to enjoy the pleasure of a\nsummer at the lake; and the\nGuild was founded to see that\nas many children as possible get\nthis chance even when their\nfamilies can\u2019t afford it.\nWon\u2019t you have a heart and\ngive your best girl and yourself\na real Valentine treat by spend\ning next Wednesday with the\nGuild at the Third Annual St.\nValentine's Dance at the Sports\nArena.\nr\nSave Electric\nBy Hazel Elgin\nWhat is the secret Cal Seiwert\nis trying to keep? We know your\nsecret, Cal. We know you cele\nbrated your birthday Monday,\nJan. 27th. Which one. Cal? Well,\nhappy birthday anyway.\nCongratulations to Elsa and\nFrank Harriman on their 3rd\nwedding anniversary Feb. 5th.\nAlso Marcelline and Alfred Gill\non their 21st wedding annivers\nary which is Feb. 8th.\nA delayed congratulations are\nin order to Pearl Colus and Zola\nTomar. They became engaged on\nDec. 25th, 1957. The engagement\nwas made complete with a beau\ntiful ring.\nA speedy recovery to Betty\nGilbert, who is home from the\nhospital now.\nWe have good news about\nClarence Likens also. He is re\nlieved to find he does not need\nan operation, just a strict diet.\nHe is hoping to be back to work\nsoon.\nI would like to see more peo\nple at our local union meetings.\nAlong with our usual business,\nwe have a five dollar door prize\neach month.\nBe a good union member and\nattend our meetings on the sec\nond Monday of every month.\nFind out what\u2019s going on in our\nshop. Don\u2019t have the idea of\nfighting just for yourself\u2014fight\nfor your brothers and sisters too.\nDon\u2019t forget the Valentine\u2019s\nDance Wednesday.\nTo Entertain At St, Valentine Dance\nDoris Thompson, Acrobatic Dancer\n5' sereptepoptnre==y===oe-xe=:\nwr 2\nY\nt*A\n\nLaDonna Krall, Vocalist\nGreetings From\nAyling\nReichert\nBy MART WYATT\nOur annual Credit Union card\nparty was quite a successful af\nfair. About one hundred persons\nspent an enjoyable evening at\nRiverside Park Shelter House on\nJan. 28th. Our annual meeting\nand election of officers for the\ncoming year preceded the party.\nYour new officers are as follows:\nBoard of Directors: Pres., C.\nBurke; V. Pres., A. Thomson;\nSecretary, V. Slane; Treasurer,\nV. Little; Member, M. Sheck\nler; Assistant Treasurer, P.\nLaderach. Credit Committee:\nChairman, C. Lehmann; Sec\nretary, M. Muller; Member, E.\nAckley. Audit Committee:\nChairman, M. Wyatt; Secre\ntary, H. Dunlap; Member, B.\nCarsten.\nA happy birthday to C. Fey on\nFeb. 4th, M. Myers, the 6th, L.\nTanner, the 8th, C. Strause, the\n14th and B. O\u2019Connor the 17th.\nAnniversary congratulations to\nDon and Rose Pantanella, 11\nyears on Feb. 1st, Ted and Marty\nBoles, 24 years, the 3rd, Earl\nand Ginny Packard, 23 years the\n8th, and Dale and Blanche Os\nwalt, 18 years the Sth.\nCongratulations to Mary Berry\non being grandma for the first\ntime to a fine grandson.\nA speedy recovery to B. Roh\nloff, in Toledo Hospital with a\nbroken leg, due to a fall on the\nice near her home.\nA happy birthday to F. Grodl\non Feb. 28th.\nAnniversary congratulations to\nClyde and Kate Appleby, 13\nyears on Feb. 7th, and to Lon\nand Fanny Abbott, 31 years on\nI the 28th.\nINSURED\ns\nE\nC\nu\nR\nE\nD\ncurrent' rate\non savings\nSAVING IS\nA GOOD HABITI\nMany thousands of Toledoans have\nfound that IT DOES PAY to save\nmonth after month the First Federal\nWay.\nI\nI\nAny day, any week, is a good time\nto start saving here at Toledo's Fed\nerally chartered Savings Association;\nFIRST FEDERAL\nSAVINGS AND LOAN ASSOCIATION\n333 ERIE STREET TOLEDO 2\nWest Side Office, Monroe at Maxwell\nEast Toledo Office, Main and 6th\nGlendale Office, Glendale and S. Detroit\nGold Dust Twins, Novelty Act\nRecord $999539560 Paid By\nBlue Cross For Care in 957\nBlue Cross payments for hos\npital services provided subscrib\ners during 1956 reached a new\nhigh when the Hospital Service\nAssociation of\nToledo\npaid\nthe\nhospitals $9,953,560.27, accord\ning to C. Arthur Collin, presi\ndent of the Board of Trustees.\nNearly $68,000,000 has been\npaid for hospital care since 1938\nwhen the Toledo Blue Cross\nPlan, which covers 12 north\nwestern\nOhio\ncounties,\nwas\nfounded, Mr. Collin said.\nPayments made to the hos\npitals in 1957 represented 95.35\nper cent of the Association\u2019s in\ncome from earned subscriber\nfees for the period, James H.\nSmith, executive director of the\nAssociation, reported.\nOperating expenses for the\nyear were $477,403.44, which\nrepresents 4.57 per cent of in\ncome. After operating expenses\nand payments to the hospitals,\nthere remained $7,838.41 to be\nplaced in a reserve fund for con\ntingencies. Other income of $95,\n478.63 also was placed in the re\nserve fund, making total addi\ntion to reserves $103,317.04, Mr.\nSmith said.\nRecord Payments Made\nRecord high payments for the\nyear probably can be traced to\nincreased hospital costs, because\n30 hospitals increased\nroom\nrates or other charges during\nthe past 12-month period, and\nmore persons were treated in\nhospitals during 1957, Blue\nCross officials said.\nIn 1956, the cost per one day\nof hospital care was pegged at\n$20.33 a day. Last year this cost\nincreased to $21.64 a day, a rise\nof $1.31 a day.\nAt the same time, the number\nof people hospitalized rose. In\n1956 there were 142.13 persons\nout of each 1,000 Blue Cross\nsubscribers admitted to the hos\npital, and in 1957 this figure was\n143.13 persons for each 1,000\nBlue Cross subscribers. While\nthis is an increase of one, it\nmeans an additional 450 hospital\npatients during a 12-month peri\nod.\nWhen the number of persons\n20th Century Whirlwinds: Willard and Jean\ngiven out-patient or emergency\ncare at the hospitals is added,\nthe incidence for the year was\n183.39 persons per 1,000 sub\nscribers, compared with 180.09\nin 1956, Mr. Smith said.\nAt the close of the year, the\nToledo Plan provided protection\nfor 432,520 persons in 12 north\nwestern Ohio counties.\nFor the first time since the\nAssociation has been in oper\nation, three hospitals received\nmore than one million dollars\nfor care given Blue Cross sub\nscribers. They are St. Vincent\u2019s,\nMercy and Toledo Hospitals.\nOn the Surface At\nSurface Combustion\nBy \u201cWHY WORRY\u201d\nWell, what do you know! Ma\nchine Shop won 2 games without\nCaptain J. K. He sure is a load,\n\"Pickles\". I think it\u2019s because he\nquit taking a shot now and then.\nSomebody told me it must be\na new moon. Roy Dressell work\ned Saturday morning, going to\nFlorida, you know.\nAll three of the top teams lost\n3 games Friday night, making\nthe league a lot closer.\nI see the Surface Combustion\nbasketball team won the first\nround in the Y. M. C. A. league\nwith 7 wins and 0 defeats. Nice\ngoing. They said they could use\na lot of moral support.\nThe Republican Recession\ncaught up with us. We had to lay\noff six steelfitters and 3 welders.\nWith union protection you had\na right to bump a fellow work\ner with less seniority, but if you\nlet the State of Ohio put the\n\u201cright-to-work\u201d law in effect,\nanything can happen. So get out\nand work against the law.\nThe Credit Union had its An\nnual Meeting Tuesday night, and\neverybody remarked how Skip\npy beat everybody in line for\nchow.\nOnly one report on ice fishing.\nPaul Magrum, LaVern Sattler,\nJuanetta Graber caught a five\ngallon pail full Saturday.\nToledo Scale\nScrihblings 1\nBy DICK SONCRANT j\nIt looks, perhaps, as if there\nmay be a slight work pickup in\nour plant. A good sign is the re\ncall of men back to the machine\nroom.\nA drop occurred in our plant\nemployment in September and it\nhas been getting worse every\nmonth.\nThe laid-off people in our\nplant would like nothing better\nthan to see a good substantial\nwork increase. Let's hope that\nthis slight work pickup turns in\nto a real raise in employment for\nthe rest of 1958.\nSarah Noel, Dept. 820; VI\nChickeral, machine room; Hazel\nWhitten, machine room, and\nLeon Moran, time keeping, are\nall back to work from sick leave.\nIt is always good to see people\nin good health again and back\non the job.\nBig news in the engineering\ndept, is the marriage of Jim\nBoardman of that dept, to Carol\nHausmann of sales dept. The\nwedding will take place tomor-,\nrow morning in St. Anthony,\nMich. Best of luck for the future\nto both of you. (See story, page\n5).\ni It is hoped that all of you\nmembers tried to make last\n.month\u2019s local meeting. The\n\u2019weather was bad and attendance\nwas down but I don\u2019t think the,\nweather can be given as a bona\nfide excuse.\nThose who attended heard the\n{reports of John Janiszewski and\nFelix Pawelczak, of the UAW\nDetroit convention. As for the I\nincrease in dues which was!\ngriped about, it is this reporter\u2019s\n_ _1_ A .__ _ _\nbelief that to fight Big Business\nour International Union MUST\nHAVE MONEY. It takes MONEY\nto fight MONEY. Any tempor\nary dues increase at this time is\njustified. If you or other mem\nbers of our union are pounding\nthe bricks, fighting for what we\ndeserve, the strike benefits from\nthe International Union will be\nquite readily accepted.\nRemember to look at the big\nsign on the lawn of the Interna\ntional and Local 12 headquarters\nat Ashland and Winthrop Sts.\nnext time you drive by.\n\u201cWe don\u2019t buy at Lasalle\u2019s,\non strike.\u201d\nWe hope every union member\nis supporting our union in this\naction.\nCatholic Church\nPlans Lectures\nA series of lectures on the\nCatholic Church, covering be\nliefs, history and doctrines, will\nbe held at the Catholic Offices\nBuilding, 1933 Spielbusch Ave\nnue, Toledo at 7:30 p.m. Monday\nand Wednesday evenings, begin\nning February 17, it is an\nnounced by Msgr. Michael J.\nDoyle, who is in charge of the\ncourse.\nThe lectures are free and carry\nno obligation, he said, and are\nopen to both Catholics and non\nCatholics. Instructors besides\nMonsignor Doyle, who is direc\ntor of Toledo Catholic Charities,\nare the Rev. Robert Blank, the\nRev. Terence Tobin, O.F.M., and\nthe Rev. Jude Rockford, O.F.M.,\ninstructors at Central Catholic\nHigh School.\nSemi-Annual Sale\n\n20% to 50% OFF\nOdd Lots Broken Sixes Discontinued Patterns\nWOMEN\nRED CROSS\nRHYTHM STEP\nJOHANSEN\nLIFE'STRIDE\nALLURES\nCHILDREN\nPOLL PARROT\nSKIP-EZE\nGERWINETTES\nSANDLER\nMEN BOYS\nBRITISH-WALKERS\nFREEMAN\nCROSBY-SQUARE\nGERBERICH\nMcCOYS\nNEWCOMB BAKER SHOES\nWESTGATE SHOPPING CENTER, CENTRAL AT SECOR\nOhio Bell\nPlans Big\nExpansion\n1\nconstruction\nOhio Bell Telephone Co.\nnounced it will commence an\n$86-million construction pro\ngram to expand its facilities in\nthe state this year.\nan\nWalter Sparling, Ohio Bell)\npresident, said that $4,900,000 of,\nthis sum will be spent in Toledo\nand $5,900,000 in the Toledo'\ndistrict.\ni\nI\nThe program will be 1\na 3-year expansion, Mr.\nling said, which will cost one-i\nquarter billion altogether. i\npart of\nSpar-'\nMr.\n\u201cclimate1\nSparling praised the\nin Ohio which, he\nsaid, made it favorable for his\ncompany to carry out such an\nambition program.\nFavorable Factors Enumerated\nFavorable factors\nr avorable factors in the\nclimate, he said, are good gov-,\nernment, a good tax situation;\nand enlightened regulation.\nI\ni\nHowever, he warned, insuffi-'\ncient earnings in the ensuing\nyears will bring the company's\nexpansion plans to a stop.\nAlthough, Mr. Sparling did\nnot refer to it specifically, Ohio\nBell has pending before the\nState Utility Commission\na re\nquest for a rate increase.\nHe declared that Ohio oei\nhas one of the best earning rec\nords of any state Bell Company\nin the country in the period\n1952 to \u201956.\nBell\nCompany In Good Position\nThe company\u2019s earnings, he\nadded, have enabled Ohio Bell\nto give the best service found\nin any state. He also predicted\nthat Ohio Bell will be the first\ncompany under American Tele\ngraph Telephone to be 100\nper cent on a dial system.\nMr. Sparling also noted that\ntechnological developments and\nautomations were enabling the\ncompany to do more work with\nless manpower.\nIn a preview of the future,\nhe declared that a new method\nof electronic switching instead\nof dialing would bring revolu\ntionary changes to subscribers.\nAmong these, he noted,\ntelephones which would wake\nup users in the morning; dialing\nby phone users of long distance\ncalls, helps to homemakers, and\nmethods by which business\ncould use the telephone to tran\nscribe inventory and other\ntransactions.\nwere\nThe Ohio Bell official r\ndieted that subscribers will Le\nable to dial long distance by the\nearly 1960s and that Toledo will\nbe the first city in the state with\nthat service.\npre\nbe\n1 Keep in mind our St. Valen\ntine\u2019s Dance on Feb. 12th.\nI\nCWA Contract Goals\nShaped by Committee\n2\n.43\n2.$\n44\nasoio\nezowCf\u201d2*%amus worr\nap, \u2022P 3 \u2014-neay\n$7\n7\nAP\n\nf'\nis *&s Pnov*7\u00ae\u2019\n\nhoomm=eron\ns*\n4\noms\n1\n3\n6\nI\n\n\nor \"art papout\"*n,\nMods \"NwtAWS Sete\n-\u201cng\nl\nECONOMIC CHART is explained to officials of the Communica\ntions Workers by Leon Keyserling (right), consultant on economic\naffairs, at the bargaining policy committee meetings in New York\nwhere negotiating goals were set From left are CW A Vice Pres.\nJohn L. Crull and Pres. Joseph A. Beirne.\nNew York\u2014Contract goals aimed at meeting the challenge of\nthe nation\u2019s lagging economy were set by the Communications\nWorkers 57-member bargaining policy committee.\nEquitable and substantial wage increases and longer vacations\nwill be demanded from the telephone industry in the next round\n01 negotiations.\nCWA Pres. Joseph A. Beirne\nsaid the bargaining sights were\n\u201cdeliberately calculated to\nbolster consumer purchasing\npower which is the key to an\nurgently needed upswing in\nthe economic cycle.\u201d\nThe union head added that\nhe was \u201cso confident of the\nreasonableness of our goals\u201d\nthat he would seek executive\nboard authorization to have\nthe Secretary of Labor appoint\na fact-finding board of emi\nnent Americans to hear the\nunion\u2019s position before they\nare presented to the industry.\nBeirne said \u201cwe will ask this\nboard to give us guidance in par\ning down our demands if the\ncommittee, in its judgment,\nthinks they should be pared.\u201d\nThe added vacation time.\nBeirne declared, \u201cwill mean an\nadditional 15 to 20 million man\nhours spread across the entire'\ncommunications industry. Spe\ncifically, we will ask for three\nweeks after 10 years of service\nand four weeks after 15 years of\nservice.\u201d\n\u2018Completely Realistic\u2019\nBeirne said the bargaining ob\njectives were completely realis\ntic. As goals for future negotia\ntions, he went on, \u201cwe have\nplaced first emphasis on the need\nfor improved pensions. Second\nly, for the future, a company\npaid health insurance program.\u201d\nHe said the Bell System is\nleast likely to feel the shock\nof the present recession be\ncause of its giant size. He said\nthe system\u2019s net profits in 1957\nwere $685 million, \"considera\nbly higher than the $616 mil\nlion the year before.\u201d\n\"The Eisenhower Adminfstra\ntion,\u201d Beirne said, \"has failed\nto act. It has failed even to ap\nply the provisions of the Em\nployment Act of 1946. When the\nPresident of the United States\nlets the economy stagnate with\nout even attempting to act, then\nthe people of America\u2014through\ntheir only effective medium, the\nunion\u2014must do those things the\nleaders of America fail to do.\u201d\nExperts Speak\nThree top-ranking authorities\nin the field of economics, utility\nrates and health insurance were\nfeatured as speakers during the\nsession. They were: Leon Key\nserling, consultant on economic\naffairs; Prof. Joseph R. Rose of\nthe Wharton school of finance.\nUniversity of Pennsylvania, and\nMartin E. Segal, consultant on\nhealth, welfare and pension pro\ngrams.\nKeyserling associated the\n\u201ccompletely outmoded and\nold-fashioned economic think\ning\u201d of the Administration\nwith \u201cthe growing economie\nrecession.\u201d He called higher\nwages a remedy for recession.\nIt is the job of consumer,\nhe added, to seek and obtain\nhigher real income now.\nProf. Rose termed utility rate\nsettling one of the most misun\nderstood subjects in the world.\nHe said that unless commissions\nare adequately supplied with\ntechnical staffs \u201ctelephone com\npanies will always out-expert\nand out-opinion\u201d complainants.\nt\n\ns\"s\nReads Just Like A History Book!\n1'\nI\nI\nTo the experienced eye, the history of\nthe world is locked in rock. That\u2019s why\nthese core samples, drilled from deep\ndown in the earth, provide essential\nclues in the never-ending search for\nmore natural gas.\nScience plays a key role in the task of\nsatisfying your ever-increasing require\nments for natural gas. Micro-geology\nand electronics assist in the drilling\noperation chemistry helps improve\nthe purity of the product... automation\nspeeds its distribution.\nToday, no effort is spared to make\ncertain that a constant supply of de\npendable, economical natural gas is\nalways available where you need it,\nwhen you need it for better living.\nNo wonder then that natural gas is the\n\"wonder fuel\u201d... modern and efficient.\nAnd it serves you best when you use it\nwith modern, automatic gas appliances.\nCOLUMBIA\nGAS\nSYSTEM\nPart of the Columbia Cas System","height":"26760","width":"19312"}}
